<br>
As far as people running out of range for that 6.0 nuke why do you even care the nuke never sticks to melees anyway /snicker.  Even if the dd did stick you would need to mez or stick str debuffs in order to hold the melee still or you would die anyway.  Honestly I don't think an enc wins any fight with a melee by playing wizard ANYWAY. I see an enc as a fantastic addition to a group pvp fight NOT a solo killer or  wanna be wizard personally.<br>
<br>
On the nuking through walls thing.  Have you ever thought of following the melee around the corner? If your gonna say but but he'll hit me! I suggest you don't stop right after the corner and instead get some space between the 2 of you before nuking. I honestly see the idea of a melee running back and forth to get a few hits as utterly ridiculous.  As a caster I think I would just back up AS I SAID and nuke them as they come around to me in fact you might consider starting your cast when you hear them come running.<br>
<br>
 Casters run around corners to get away from melees all the time.  Then start nuking from out of sight.  In fact a typical strategy involves making the melee lose track of you then nuking through a wall.  What I'm asking for is to require both parties, caster and melee to have an awareness of their targets position in order to attack and to give both parties a way to respond to that attack.  In other words a level playing field.  You complain about the idea of melees using walls and branching coridors to get out of line of sight and avoid being nuked when casters use the same strategy as it is.  The only differnce is that melees can't attack you from around that corner or behind that wall if he manages to escape behind it.  I would expect both parties to be able to deal with not being able to hit the other until they come within just fine and the pvp experience to be more interesting for it.  In fact a good pvper allready knows he has a much better chance of a kill if he keeps his quary in sight.<br>
<br>
Next as far as blatant exaggeration.  I think correct me if I'm wrong here but I'm under the impression that a 55 mage would have something like 1.2 or 1.4k hp (counting 250hp self buff and assuming pog or similar quality gear) and as to a 55 rogue having close to 3k hp don't make me laugh as a 55 rogue in good gear I have 1650hp in resist gear and only a bit higher in hp ac gear. Good gear being pog armor, dwarf quest armor, epic that sort of thing.  No tov stuff here. <br>
<br>
Btw double 400s are pretty uncommon hell I almost never hit sitting people for more than a total of 600.  Not only that but backstabs can be avoided by not turning your back. In addition our dmg output is compensation for having low hp and ac so get over it. Btw FYI as far as doubles you have to figure that only like 1/2 of backstabs are doubles and often enough either the 1st or the 2nd misses (unless your sitting).  Double backstab is great but melee hits follow different rules than spells and you can't act like a rogue backstabs for double 400s every 7 seconds.  If we could our unbuffed dps would be 114 just from backstabs at 55!  In fact I think it goes something like...<br>
<br>
20% no hits landed<br>
60% 1 hit landed<br>
20% 2 hits landed<br>
<br>
And giving the max dmg as the average is so completely false its ridiculous.  Saying a rogue can double for 400 is nothing like saying a caster can nuke for 800.  A double 400 is actually more like getting a nice crit.<br>
<br>
<br>
You present yourself as the disadvaged party and claim a need for cheap strategies in order to survive but I as someone who has been through a lot of pvp say this is BS.  As a rogue lvl 55 is actually feeling a lot more balanced to me but nothing like being overpowered.<br>
<br>
It occurs to me that people who do badly at pvp are often those who don't start the fight.  The person who starts the fight no matter if its with a sitting double bs or a nice nuke and an attack from a pet has quite an advantage. Might wanna try it some time.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
